        <h2 style="color: rgba(255, 0, 0, 0.564);">In This Website we learn how to convert one form of Temperature into another form and we will study more about temperature.</h2>
   <br><br><br>
        <h1 style="text-align: center;">Origins of Temperature Scales</h1>

        <h2>Celsius</h2>
        <p>Celsius is the most widely used temperature scale in the world today. It was developed by Swedish astronomer and physicist Anders Celsius in the 18th century.</p>

        <h2>Fahrenheit</h2>
        <p>The Fahrenheit temperature scale was developed by Polish-German physicist and engineer Daniel Gabriel Fahrenheit. In 1724 Fahrenheit created the mercury-in-glass thermometer which had a standardized temperature scale and greater accuracy than existing thermometers.</p>

        <h2>Kelvin</h2>
        <p>The Kelvin scale is also called the absolute temperature scale. William Thomson, known as Lord Kelvin, proposed the idea of an absolute temperature scale based on absolute zero, where molecular motion stops.</p>

        <h2>Rankine</h2>
        <p>The Rankine scale was developed in the 19th century by Scottish physicist and engineer William John Macquorn Rankine. Rankine's scale is related to the Kelvin scale, where the Kelvin degree is the same size as the Rankine degree. Rankine begins at absolute zero.</p>

        <h2>Réaumur</h2>
        <p>The Réaumur temperature scale is named for René-Antoine Ferchault de Réaumur. It divides the temperature range between the freezing and boiling points of water into 80 equal parts.</p>

        <div class="conversion-table">
            <h1 style="text-align: center;">Temperature Conversion Formulas</h1>
            <table>
                <tr>
                    <th>Scale</th>
                    <th>Conversion to Celsius (°C)</th>
                    <th>Conversion to Kelvin (K)</th>
                    <th>Conversion to Fahrenheit (°F)</th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Celsius (°C)</td>
                    <td>Same as Celsius</td>
                    <td>Celsius + 273.15</td>
                    <td>(Celsius × 9/5) + 32</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Fahrenheit (°F)</td>
                    <td>(Fahrenheit - 32) × 5/9</td>
                    <td>((Fahrenheit - 32) × 5/9) + 273.15</td>
                    <td>Same as Fahrenheit</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Kelvin (K)</td>
                    <td>Kelvin - 273.15</td>
                    <td>Same as Kelvin</td>
                    <td>((Kelvin - 273.15) × 9/5) + 32</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
