        <h1>Tips for Temperature Conversion</h1>
        <ul>
            <li>When converting temperatures, remember to use parentheses to ensure the correct order of operations.</li>
            <li>Absolute zero is the lowest possible temperature, which is 0 K (Kelvin), -273.15 °C (Celsius), or -459.67 °F (Fahrenheit).</li>
            <li>When dealing with scientific calculations, it's often best to use the Kelvin scale because it starts from absolute zero and is widely used in scientific research.</li>
        </ul>
